-- ─── 1. Alexa ASCI (Trust & Safety) ────────────────────────────────────────

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{
  "summary": "Design a multi-layer trust & safety system for Alexa+ LLM responses: safety taxonomy, 3-layer real-time pipeline, LLM-as-judge evaluation, and continuous drift monitoring.",
  "outline": [
    "Phase 1 — Requirements: clarify response types, user demographics (COPPA for children), latency budget, regulatory frameworks (FTC, EU AI Act)",
    "Phase 2 — Safety Taxonomy: Tier 1 (block: harmful, PII, CSAM), Tier 2 (flag: medical advice, misinformation), Tier 3 (monitor: bias, quality drift)",
    "Phase 3 — Architecture: 3-layer pipeline — rule-based blocklist (microseconds), ML classifier (10-20ms), LLM safety judge (100-200ms); hybrid pre/post-generation evaluation",
    "Phase 4 — Evaluation: offline test suites per risk category, adversarial red-teaming per layer, false positive vs false negative cost tradeoffs",
    "Phase 5 — Production: drift monitoring by category, locale compliance rollout, rollback triggers, pre-computed safety scores for common responses"
  ],
  "full_response": "I would start by clarifying scope. What types of Alexa+ responses are in scope — factual answers, creative generation, task completion, multi-turn conversation? Who are the users — the system must be significantly stricter for children''s interactions given COPPA obligations. What''s the latency budget — can safety evaluation add 200ms, or does it need to be near-zero? What regulatory frameworks apply — FTC guidelines, COPPA for children, EU AI Act if we''re deploying globally?\n\nThe safety taxonomy defines what we''re detecting. I''d organize it by severity. Tier 1 — block immediately: explicit harmful content, instructions for dangerous activities, PII leakage (SSN, credit cards via regex), CSAM. Tier 2 — flag for review: medical or legal advice that could cause harm, potential misinformation on high-stakes topics (health, finance, elections), culturally sensitive content. Tier 3 — monitor and learn: bias patterns, subtle stereotyping, quality degradation, off-topic responses. For children''s interactions, I''d push Tier 2 content into Tier 1.\n\nThe architecture is a three-layer pipeline. Layer 1: rule-based filters run in microseconds — blocklists, regex patterns for PII, hard blocks on known dangerous query-response patterns. This catches easy cases with near-zero latency. Layer 2: a lightweight ML classifier — distilled BERT trained on human-labeled safety data — runs in 10-20ms and outputs a safety probability per risk category. Layer 3: an LLM safety judge with a structured rubric, reserved for the ambiguous zone between Layer 2''s auto-pass and auto-block thresholds. Based on my experience at Walmart, only 2-5% of traffic lands in this ambiguous zone, so the expensive LLM call is rare.\n\nThe key design decision is pre-generation vs post-generation evaluation. Pre-generation (streaming token filter) allows early stopping but requires streaming evaluation infrastructure. Post-generation (evaluating the complete response) is simpler but adds latency. I''d propose a hybrid: Layer 1 runs as a streaming filter on output tokens, Layer 2 evaluates the complete response before delivery, and Layer 3 runs asynchronously — results feed monitoring and model improvement rather than blocking delivery for borderline cases.\n\nFor evaluation, I''d build offline test suites with known-unsafe and known-safe examples per risk category, and adversarial red-teaming sets designed to bypass each individual layer. The critical tradeoff: false positives (safe content blocked) erode trust and Alexa engagement; false negatives (harmful content delivered) carry reputational and regulatory risk. I''d set thresholds to minimize false negatives first, then tune to reduce false positive rate via human review queue.\n\nIn production: drift monitoring tracks safety flag rate by category and false positive rate — a sudden shift indicates either a change in the underlying Alexa+ LLM or a new attack pattern. Locale compliance requires separate taxonomy versions per region, with phased rollout and region-specific red-teaming. Rollback trigger: if Tier 1 miss rate spikes above threshold, auto-rollback to the previous pipeline version. For cost efficiency, pre-compute safety scores for common query-response pairs and cache them — most Alexa queries are highly repetitive."
}'::jsonb
WHERE category = 'design' AND subcategory = 'Alexa ASCI';


-- ─── 2. Alexa RAG ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{
  "summary": "Design a RAG system for Alexa+: knowledge ingestion pipeline, hybrid dense+sparse retrieval, cross-encoder reranking, faithfulness grounding, and freshness management.",
  "outline": [
    "Phase 1 — Requirements: knowledge domains (product catalog, world knowledge, real-time), 100-150ms retrieval budget, zero hallucination tolerance for product facts, static vs dynamic vs real-time tiers",
    "Phase 2 — Ingestion & Indexing: semantic chunking, domain-tuned bi-encoder embeddings, FAISS HNSW + Elasticsearch/BM25 hybrid index, metadata filtering",
    "Phase 3 — Retrieval: hybrid BM25 + dense ANN merged via Reciprocal Rank Fusion, cross-encoder reranker on top-50, voice query normalization, multi-hop decomposition",
    "Phase 4 — Grounding & Faithfulness: grounding prompt constraints, claim-level citation, faithfulness scorer, refusal when confidence < threshold",
    "Phase 5 — Production: incremental index updates with hash-based change detection, query routing logic (RAG vs parametric), hallucination rate monitoring, multi-turn context"
  ],
  "full_response": "I''d start with requirements. Alexa+ needs to ground responses across multiple knowledge domains: Amazon product catalog (structured, changes frequently), general world knowledge (large, mostly static), and real-time data like weather or stock prices (live API calls, not indexable). The latency constraint is severe — voice assistant end-to-end must feel instant, which means RAG retrieval and reranking must complete in 100-150ms total. Hallucination tolerance varies by domain: product specs must be exact (wrong RAM spec sends the user to the wrong product), while conversational responses have more tolerance for imprecision.\n\nThe knowledge ingestion pipeline: crawl and ingest source documents, clean and normalize, then chunk. I''d use semantic chunking rather than fixed-size windows — split on natural boundaries (paragraphs, sections) to preserve context. Each chunk is embedded with a domain-tuned bi-encoder (E5-large or a model fine-tuned on Amazon QA pairs). The index is dual: FAISS HNSW for dense retrieval (semantic similarity), Elasticsearch for sparse BM25 (exact keyword match). Metadata stored alongside each chunk: source domain, freshness timestamp, locale. This enables filtered retrieval — for a product question, restrict to catalog domain; for a general question, open up to all domains.\n\nThe retrieval pipeline is two-stage. Stage 1: hybrid retrieval — run dense ANN on FAISS and BM25 on Elasticsearch in parallel, merge results via Reciprocal Rank Fusion. This combines semantic understanding with exact match strength. Stage 2: a cross-encoder reranker scores the top-50 candidates jointly with the query — same architecture as the cross-encoder I used for product retrieval, which gave +0.192 NDCG improvement. The reranker selects the top-5 passages to provide as context. For voice queries, ASR transcripts contain errors, so I''d add a normalization step before retrieval — correct obvious misspellings, expand abbreviations, handle homophones.\n\nFor multi-hop queries like ''is the director of that show I liked also on any Amazon originals,'' I''d decompose into sub-queries: (1) identify the show from conversation history, (2) retrieve director, (3) search Amazon originals for that director. A query decomposer (lightweight LLM call) handles this.\n\nGrounding and faithfulness: the generation prompt explicitly constrains the LLM to only use the retrieved passages — ''Answer using only the following context. If the answer is not in the context, say you don''t know.'' For each response, a lightweight faithfulness scorer (fine-tuned NLI model) checks whether each claim in the response is entailed by at least one passage. If faithfulness score < 0.8, we either regenerate with stronger constraints or fall back to ''I don''t have reliable information on that.'' Claims in the response are tagged with passage IDs for citation, enabling source attribution in the UI.\n\nIn production: knowledge freshness via incremental updates. A crawler checks source documents on a rolling schedule; hash-based fingerprinting detects changes and re-embeds only modified chunks. Query routing logic decides at inference time: if the query is a well-known factoid that the LLM handles reliably AND latency is tight, route to parametric. If the query involves product specifics, recent events, or anything where hallucination risk is high, route through RAG. Monitoring tracks retrieval hit rate, faithfulness score distribution, and hallucination rate (sampled via the judge). Multi-turn context: carry the top retrieved passages across turns within a session so follow-up questions don''t require a full re-retrieval."
}'::jsonb
WHERE category = 'design' AND subcategory = 'Alexa RAG';


-- ─── 3. Prime Video Personalization ─────────────────────────────────────────

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{
  "summary": "Design a personalized video recommendation system: two-tower candidate generation with multimodal embeddings, cross-encoder ranking with multi-objective optimization, cold-start strategies, and production monitoring.",
  "outline": [
    "Phase 1 — Requirements: surfaces (homepage, post-play, genre rows), primary metric = watch-through rate, secondary = session length + subscription renewal, scale = 200M+ users / 10K+ titles",
    "Phase 2 — Architecture: two-tower ANN (top-500) → cross-encoder ranking (top-20) → multi-objective blending → serving with 1-hour TTL cache",
    "Phase 3 — Two-Tower Deep Dive: user tower encodes watch sequence + temporal context; content tower uses multimodal embeddings (synopsis + CLIP trailer/poster); InfoNCE training with hard negatives; FAISS HNSW index",
    "Phase 4 — Ranking & Multi-Objective: cross-encoder with behavioral + contextual + business features; scalarized score = engagement + diversity_bonus + freshness_bonus + explore_bonus; Thompson sampling for exploration; weights tuned per surface",
    "Phase 5 — Cold-Start, A/B Testing & Production: new user → acquisition channel segmentation → personalized; new title → metadata-only embedding + 2-week exploration boost; A/B with watch-through + retention both required; embedding staleness alerts"
  ],
  "full_response": "I''d start by clarifying surfaces and success metrics. Are we optimizing the homepage hero, genre rows, post-play autoplay, ''more like this'' — each surface has different user intent and signal density. The primary metric should be watch-through rate: the fraction of a title actually watched. Click-through is cheap — a misleading thumbnail can generate clicks that damage trust. Secondary metrics: session length (are users staying?), cross-genre exploration rate (are they discovering new things?), and subscription renewal as the ultimate north star. Scale: 200M+ users, 10K+ titles, and real-time personalization required.\n\nThe high-level architecture: candidate generation retrieves the top-500 titles from the full catalog in <20ms, ranking scores each candidate and selects the top-20 for the UI, multi-objective blending adjusts for diversity and freshness, then serving caches results per user with a 1-hour TTL invalidated on new watch events.\n\nThe two-tower model is the core of candidate generation. The user tower encodes: watch sequence (recent titles the user completed, genres, watch completion percentages), temporal features (time of day, day of week, device type), and demographic context. The content tower encodes: genre, cast, director, synopsis embedding, and critically for video — a multimodal visual embedding from trailer keyframes and poster images using a vision-language model like CLIP. Text alone misses visual style, which is a strong user preference signal for video. Both towers project to a shared 128-dimensional space trained with InfoNCE loss on (user, watched_video) positive pairs. Hard negative mining is critical: include titles the user viewed but didn''t watch or abandoned — these teach the model the difference between a click and genuine engagement. I served a similar architecture at Walmart where this improved NDCG by +0.192. We maintain a FAISS HNSW index updated hourly.\n\nRanking uses a cross-encoder that jointly processes user context and video features. Features include: retrieval score from the two-tower, temporal features (time since the user last watched this genre), social signals (trending in the user''s demographic), and business signals (Prime Original promotion, licensing window urgency). The multi-objective score is: final = w1*engagement + w2*diversity_bonus + w3*freshness_bonus + w4*explore_bonus. The diversity bonus rewards genres the user hasn''t watched in >30 days — preventing filter bubbles. The freshness bonus promotes recently released content. The exploration bonus uses Thompson sampling to promote content the system is uncertain about for this user. Weights are tuned per surface via online experiments — the homepage benefits from more diversity than post-play autoplay.\n\nCold-start: for new users, start with popularity-based recommendations segmented by acquisition channel — a user who signed up for a specific show gets very different initial recommendations than one who came from a generic ad. After 5-10 viewing sessions, transition to fully personalized. For new titles, the content tower produces embeddings from metadata alone (synopsis, cast, genre, trailer). For the first two weeks after release, the title gets an exploration boost that decays as engagement data accumulates.\n\nA/B testing: pre-registered hypotheses, holdout groups stratified by user tenure. We only ship if both watch-through rate AND subscription retention improve — engagement gains that hurt retention are pyrrhic. Monitoring: embedding staleness alerts (is the FAISS index stale?), recommendation diversity by user cohort (catching filter bubbles), and watch-through rate by content category to detect serving failures."
}'::jsonb
WHERE category = 'design' AND subcategory = 'Prime Video Personalization';


-- ─── 4. Amazon Search ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{
  "summary": "Design Amazon product search ML ranking: query understanding, hybrid BM25 + dense retrieval, two-stage L1/L2 ranking with LTR and cross-encoder, personalization layer, ad integration, and fairness monitoring.",
  "outline": [
    "Phase 1 — Requirements: query types (text/voice/image), success metric = add-to-cart + purchase rate, scale = billions of products / millions QPS / 100ms SLA, personalization required",
    "Phase 2 — Architecture: query understanding (10ms) → hybrid retrieval top-1000 (20ms) → L1 GBDT ranking top-100 (30ms) → L2 cross-encoder top-30 (30ms) → post-ranking ads + diversity (10ms)",
    "Phase 3 — Retrieval: BM25 exact match + dense bi-encoder product embeddings (title + attributes) merged via Reciprocal Rank Fusion; query expansion + spelling correction; FAISS HNSW sharded by category",
    "Phase 4 — L1/L2 Ranking & Personalization: L1 GBDT trained on purchase/add-to-cart labels; L2 cross-encoder with deep text matching; personalization via user purchase/browse history embeddings + real-time session signals",
    "Phase 5 — Ads, Production & Fairness: sponsored products pass relevance gate before insertion; latency monitoring per stage; fairness monitoring by seller tier; A/B with purchase rate + fairness both required"
  ],
  "full_response": "I''d start with requirements. Query types: text is the dominant modality (80%), voice queries are growing (15%) and have different ASR-induced noise, image search is emerging (5%). The success metric is not click-through — it''s add-to-cart rate and purchase rate. CTR is a noisy proxy; a misleading image drives clicks that don''t convert and erodes trust. Scale: billions of products in the catalog, millions of QPS, 100ms p99 latency SLA end-to-end. Personalization: the same query ''running shoes'' should return very different results for a marathoner versus a casual walker based on purchase and browsing history.\n\nThe full pipeline with latency budgets: query understanding (10ms) takes the raw query and outputs a normalized, enriched query. Candidate retrieval (20ms) returns the top-1000 products from the full catalog. L1 ranking (30ms) uses a lightweight GBDT to score the top-1000 and select the top-100. L2 ranking (30ms) uses a heavy cross-encoder with full features to score top-100 and select top-30. Post-ranking (10ms) injects sponsored products, enforces diversity constraints, applies business rules. Total: 100ms.\n\nQuery understanding handles spelling correction (''iphone charger'' → ''iPhone USB-C cable''), query normalization, intent classification (product search vs informational query vs brand navigation), and entity extraction (brand, product type, attributes). For voice queries, ASR transcripts are noisier — extra normalization and phonetic fuzzy matching. For image queries, a vision encoder maps the image to a query embedding in the same space as product embeddings.\n\nCandidate retrieval uses hybrid sparse + dense. BM25 in Elasticsearch handles exact keyword match — strong for rare queries and specific product codes. The dense bi-encoder embeds product titles, descriptions, and structured attributes (category, brand, price range) into a shared 768-dim space. At query time, the query is embedded and ANN search runs on FAISS HNSW — sharded by product category to stay within latency. Reciprocal Rank Fusion merges BM25 and dense candidates. Query expansion runs before retrieval: add synonyms, brand aliases, and related terms to improve recall on tail queries.\n\nL1 ranking is a GBDT (XGBoost) — fast, interpretable, handles sparse features. Training signal: (query, product, label) triples with labels purchase=3, add-to-cart=2, click=1, impression=0. Features: BM25 score, semantic similarity from retrieval, product quality signals (rating, review count), seller signals (fulfillment speed, return rate). L2 ranking is a cross-encoder transformer that jointly encodes query and product title/description for deep text matching — same architecture I used for product retrieval. L2 features add behavioral signals: CTR and purchase rate for this exact query-product pair (stored in a feature store), temporal freshness, and personalization: the user''s purchase/browse history is encoded as a 128-dim embedding and concatenated to L2 features. Real-time session signals (what they''ve viewed in the last 30 minutes) are computed on-the-fly from the event stream.\n\nAd integration: sponsored products must pass a minimum relevance score threshold before being inserted — this prevents pure pay-to-play from degrading search quality. Ad slots are pre-allocated (positions 1, 5, 9) and filled with sponsored products that pass the relevance gate. If no sponsored product meets the threshold, organic results fill those positions.\n\nFor fairness monitoring: track add-to-cart rate and purchase rate by seller tier monthly. If small sellers are systematically disadvantaged at equal product quality, this suggests the ranking model has learned a spurious correlation (e.g., brand name as a proxy for quality). Fix: add seller tier as a regularization constraint during L2 training, or apply a fairness-aware re-ranking step. A/B testing framework: pre-registered metrics, holdout groups, ship only if purchase rate improves AND fairness metrics don''t degrade. Latency monitoring per pipeline stage — alerts when any stage exceeds its budget, enabling targeted optimization."
}'::jsonb
WHERE category = 'design' AND subcategory = 'Amazon Search';
